Tutorial 8.1: Multiple regression on the fish tank dataset

As an exercise on multiple regression, we will analyse the fish tank dataset.

1 Fish tank dataset

In this experiments 96 fish (dojofish, goldfish and zebrafish) were placed separately in a tank with two liters of water and a certain dose (in mg) of a certain poison EI-43,064. The resistance of the fish a against the poison was measured as the amount of minutes the fish survived upon adding the poison (Surv_time, in minutes). Additionally, the weightt of each fish was measured.

2 Goal

In this tutorial, we will study the association between dose and survival time, while correcting for weight and species, by using a multiple regression model.

Read the required libraries

library(GGally)
library(tidyverse)
library(car)

poison <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/GTPB/PSLS20/master/data/poison.csv")

4 Data tidying

We can see a couple of things in the data that can be improved upon:

  1. Capitalize the fist column name
  2. Set the Species column as a factor
  3. Change the speciec factor levels from 0, 1 and 2 to Dojofish, Goldfish and Zebrafish. Hint: use the fct_recode function.
  4. Add the variable log.Surv_time: we already saw in previous tutorials that this transfromation is required to obtain normally distributed data.
poison <- poison %>%
  rename("Species" = "species") %>%
  mutate(Species = as.factor(Species)) %>%
  mutate(Species = fct_recode(Species, Dojofish = "0", Goldfish = "1", Zebrafish = "2")) %>%
  mutate(log.Surv_time = log(Surv_time))

5 Data exploration

In a previous tutorial, we already studied the effect of dose on (the logarithm of) suvival time. There, we did not account for the fact that fish of the same species and/or fish of similar weight will probably reacht similarly to the poison.

When we expect the data more closely, we see that these factors do indeed matter.

poison %>% dplyr::select(Species,Weight,Dose,log.Surv_time) %>% ggpairs()

We can see several interesting associations:

  • Survival time seems to be strongly associated with dose, species and weight.
  • There is a strong, positive association between log survival time and weight.
  • For low weights, the log survival time slope seems to flatten.
  • The weigths are not equally distributed over the different doses.
  • There is an association between species and weight.

Some additional visualizations:

The log survival time is different for different species.

The researchers assume, based on the data exploration, that the dose effect on survival varies between different species. As such, a good model should have an interaction effect between dose and species. We will also include an interaction between weight and species.

6 Analysis

6.1 Assess full model with main and interaction effects

\[y_i=\beta_0+\beta_d x_{id} + \beta_w x_{iw} +\beta_{sg} x_{isg} +\beta_{sz} x_{isz} + \beta_{d-sg} x_{id}x_{isg} + \beta_{d-sz} x_{id}x_{isz} + \beta_{w-sg} x_{iw}x_{isg} + \beta_{w-sz} x_{iw}x_{isz} + \epsilon_i,\]

with \(x_{isg}\) and \(x_{isz}\) the dummy variables pointing at goldfish and zebrafish, respectively. Dojofish are the reference class, i.e. when \(x_{isg}=0\) en \(x_{isz}=0\).

We assume \(\epsilon_i \text{ i.i.d. } N(0,\sigma^2)\).

We will predict the dose response for each species.

\[\begin{array}{ll} \text{dojofish } (x_{isg}=0\text{ and }x_{isz}=0):&E[y\vert \text{dojofish}]=\beta_0+\beta_d x_{id} + \beta_w x_{iw}\\ \text{goldfish } (x_{isg}=1\text{ and }x_{isz}=0):&E[y\vert \text{goldfish}]=\beta_0+\beta_{sg}+(\beta_d+ \beta_{d-sa}) x_{id} + (\beta_w+\beta_{w-sg}) x_{iw}\\ \text{zebrafish } (x_{isg}=0\text{ and }x_{isz}=1):&E[y\vert \text{zebrafish}]=\beta_0+\beta_{sz}+(\beta_d+ \beta_{d-sz}) x_{id} + (\beta_w+\beta_{w-sz}) x_{iw}\\ \end{array}\]

  • The species main effect makes sure that each species will have its own intercept in the model. (\(\beta_0\), \(\beta_0 + \beta_{sg}\), \(\beta_0+\beta_{sz}\))

  • The interaction between species and dose ensures that the dose effect (slope) can be different between different species. (\(\beta_d\), \(\beta_d+\beta_{d-sg}\), \(\beta_d+\beta_{d-sz}\))

  • The interaction between species and weight makes sure that the weigth effect (slope) can be different for different species. (\(\beta_w\), \(\beta_w+\beta_{w-sg}\), \(\beta_w+\beta_{w-sz}\)

Note: if we would not use the interaction terms, but still wanted to model the data correctly, we could fit a separate model for every species. The advantage of modelling the data for all species together, is that we are using all of the data to estimate the residual variances.

Let us now fit the full multiple regression model:

lm_full <- lm(log.Surv_time~ Species + Dose + Weight + Species:Dose + Species:Weight, data=poison)
plot(lm_full)

6.1.1 Assumptions

List assumptions:

  1. The observations are independent of each other
  2. Linearity between the response and predictor variable
  3. The residues of the model must be normally distributed
  4. Homoscedasticity of the data

Asses:

  1. The first assumption is met. As discussed a previous tutorial, there are patterns of relatedness in the data: We expect that fish of the same species have a more similar response to the poison as compared to fish of another species. Equivalently, we expect that fish of the same weight have a more similar response to the poison as compared to fish of different weight.

Our model now specifically accounts for this. We do not expect that there are inducing additional dependcies in the data.

  1. The linearity assumption is met.

  2. The normality assumption is met. There is a small deviation from normality, but given the relatively large dataset (96 observations) we do not expect this to cause major problems. In addition, we have a relativwly large dataset, so we could start relying on the central limit theorem).

  3. The homoscedasticity assumption is met.

We clearly see that the interaction effect between species and dose, which ensures that the dose effect (slope) can be different between different species, does not have a significant contribution to the linear regression model after correcting for the other variables in that model. As such, this interaction effect could be omitted from the model.

Here, we see that the interaction term between weight and species remains significant in the model. As such, we will retain this interaction. This model will thus be our final model.

6.2.1 Main model

Before we interpret the output, we must first note that while the main effect for species does not appear significant in this model, this is merely beccause it’s effect is absorbed in the species:weight interaction term. Indeed, if we would work with a model only consisting of the three main effects, the species term would be extremely significant:

lm_main <- lm(log.Surv_time ~ Dose + Weight + Species, data=poison)
Anova(lm_main, type = "III")

6.2.2 Interpretation of the reduced model

The model parameters can be interpreted in terms of the average, log-transformed survival time.

  • The interpretation of the intercept (average log-transformed survival time for dose = 0 mg, weight = 0 g and species = dojofish) is not very useful, as this dose and wieght values fall outside the range for which we constructed the model.

  • Dose main effect: The log survival time is, on average, 0.583 lower if the dose is increased with 1mg, after correcting for weight and species differences.

  • Weight main effect: The log survival time is, on average, 0.739 higher for fish that weigh 1 additional gram, after dose and species correction.

  • SpeciesGoldfish: The log survival time is, on average, 0.237 lower for goldfish than for dojofish, after dose and weight correction. The SpeciesZebrafish term is interpreted analogously.

  • SpeciesGoldfish:Weight interaction; the weight effect on the log survival time is, on average, 0.336 more positive for goldfish than for dojofish, after dose, weight and species correction.

7 Conclusion

  • Dose main effect: The geometric mean of the survival time is a factor 0.558 (95% CI [0.451; 0.690]) lower if the dose is increased with 1mg, after correcting for weight and species differences.This effect is extremely significant (p<0.001) on the 5% significance level.

  • Weight main effect: The geometric mean of the survival time is a factor 2.093 (95% CI [1.290; 3.397]) higher if the fish weight is increased with 1g, after correcting for dose and species differences.This effect is extremely significant (p<0.001) on the 5% significance level.

  • Zebrafish weight interaction: The weight effect on the geometric mean of the survival time is a factor 0.366 (95% CI [0.149; 0.952]) lower for zebrafish as for goldfish. In other words, the protective effect of weight is stronger for goldfish than for zebrafish. This effect is significant (0.0354) on the 5% significance level.

  • We did not find enough evidence to infer significance of the other model parameters.
